INSERT INTO contributions (idea_id, author_id, content, decision_log, status, view_count, submitted_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES
(2, 3, E'# KidGate: QR-Based Daycare Check-In & Attendance Platform\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nKidGate is a lightweight SaaS platform that replaces paper sign-in sheets at daycares with QR-code-based check-in and checkout. Parents scan a unique QR code at drop-off and pickup using their phone — no app download required. Teachers receive instant push notifications and classroom headcounts update automatically. Directors get daily attendance reports and licensing-compliant records stored in the cloud. KidGate targets daycare centers serving 150–300 children, a segment where regulatory attendance documentation is mandatory but existing tools are either too expensive or too complex.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Licensed US daycare centers | ~86,000 | NARA / ChildCare.gov 2024 |\n| Centers with 150–300 enrolled children | ~18,000 | Estimated 21% of total |\n| % still using paper sign-in sheets | ~58% | NAEYC member survey 2023 |\n| Average daily check-in events per 200-child center | 400 (drop-off + pickup) | Internal estimate |\n| State licensing requirement: attendance records kept | 60–90 days (varies by state) | NARA compliance guide |\n| Average fine for missing attendance records | $250–$2,500 per incident | State licensing boards |\n| Existing digital check-in adoption rate (SMB daycares) | ~22% | Brightwheel user data |\n| US childcare management software TAM | $1.1B | Grand View Research 2024 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Brightwheel | All-in-one childcare management | 150,000+ centers | Feature-rich, strong brand | $200+/mo, overwhelming for small directors |\n| HiMama | Parent engagement + daily reports | 8,000+ centers | Good parent UX | No QR check-in, Canada-focused |\n| Procare Software | Center management + billing | 37,000+ | Deep billing/accounting | Desktop legacy software, complex setup |\n| Tadpoles | Activity reports + check-in | 5,000+ | Simple parent app | Weak director reporting, no real-time alerts |\n| Paper sign-in sheet | Manual | ~50,000 centers | $0 cost | No alerts, compliance risk, illegible records |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Patricia, 51, Daycare Director, Columbus OH**\nPatricia runs a 220-child center licensed under Ohio ODJFS. She dreads state inspections because her staff sometimes forgets to get a parent signature at pickup. She has been fined once ($500) for an incomplete record. She wants a system that makes compliance automatic and gives her a printable attendance log on demand.\n\n**Persona 2 — Marcus, 38, Owner/Director, Church-Based Daycare, Atlanta GA**\nMarcus runs a 170-child daycare attached to his church. He has three teachers per room and no dedicated admin staff. He needs check-in to work even when the internet goes down (the church has spotty WiFi). Offline mode is non-negotiable for him.\n\n**Persona 3 — Jennifer, 44, Co-Director, Cooperative Daycare, Portland OR**\nJennifer''s co-op has parents volunteering as aides. She needs a system that logs which parent volunteers are on-site (for licensing ratio requirements) as well as which children are present. She is tech-savvy and would pay more for an API to sync attendance data into their QuickBooks-based payroll system.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Per-child QR code generation | Unique, printable QR code on ID card or key fob for each enrolled child |\n| P0 | Mobile web check-in scanner | PWA scanner page for teachers'' tablets/phones — no app install required |\n| P0 | Real-time classroom headcount | Live count of present children per room, visible to all staff on shift |\n| P0 | Instant teacher notification | Push notification (web push + SMS fallback) on each check-in/out event |\n| P0 | Daily attendance report (PDF) | Auto-generated, state-format-compliant report for each classroom |\n| P1 | Authorized pickup list | Each child has a list of approved adults; alert if unrecognized person attempts pickup |\n| P1 | Parent self-check-in portal | Parents can pre-authorize early or late pickup via mobile web |\n| P1 | Offline mode | Local PWA cache stores check-in events when offline; syncs on reconnect |\n| P2 | Volunteer/aide attendance tracking | Same QR system logs parent volunteer hours |\n| P2 | QuickBooks/Gusto export | Attendance data export for payroll and subsidy billing purposes |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Node.js 20 + Express\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15 (attendance records) + Redis (real-time headcounts)\n- PWA: React 18 + Workbox (service worker for offline cache)\n- Push Notifications: Web Push API + Twilio SMS fallback\n- PDF Generation: Puppeteer (headless Chrome) for state-compliant reports\n- Auth: JWT + refresh tokens (staff login), magic link QR tokens (parent portal)\n- Hosting: Render.com (MVP) → AWS Fargate + RDS (scale)\n- File Storage: AWS S3 (attendance PDFs)\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nEach QR code encodes a signed JWT containing child ID and center ID. When a staff tablet scans the code, the PWA validates the token locally (offline-capable) and queues a check-in event. On reconnect, the service worker flushes the queue to the backend via a batch endpoint. Redis maintains real-time headcount per room, updated on every check-in/out. A nightly cron job generates PDF attendance reports and stores them in S3, available for director download or automated email delivery. All records are retained for 180 days by default (exceeds all state requirements).\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly SaaS subscription | $89/mo per center (up to 300 children) | 75% |\n| Compliance report archiving | $19/mo for extended 3-year retention + audit export | 12% |\n| SMS notification add-on | $14/mo for unlimited parent SMS alerts | 8% |\n| Setup & data migration | One-time $149 per center | 5% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | QR code generation + PWA scanner + PostgreSQL schema + basic headcount display |\n| M2 | Push notifications + teacher dashboard + PDF attendance report generation |\n| M3 | Offline mode (Workbox) + authorized pickup list + parent portal |\n| M4 | Billing (Stripe) + compliance archive tier + onboard 20 pilot centers |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying daycare centers | 20 | 80 |\n| MRR | $1,780 | $7,400 |\n| Avg. check-in events processed/day/center | 380 | 390 |\n| Offline sync error rate | <0.5% | <0.2% |\n| Director NPS | 40 | 55 |\n| State inspection compliance rate (centers using KidGate) | 100% | 100% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| State licensing format changes requiring report updates | Medium | High | Parameterized report templates; dedicated compliance update SLA |\n| QR code duplication/spoofing | Low | High | Signed JWT tokens with 30-second expiry for check-in scans |\n| Offline sync conflicts (duplicate check-ins) | Medium | Medium | Idempotency key on each event; last-write-wins with conflict log |\n| Center director resistance to software adoption | High | Medium | Free 60-day trial; offer white-glove setup call |\n| COPPA compliance for storing child data | Low | Critical | No PII in QR tokens; data encrypted at rest; COPPA-compliant privacy policy |\n', '[{"step":"tech_approach","decision":"PWA (no native app)","reason":"No app download removes biggest adoption barrier for parents; PWA works on all smartphones"},{"step":"offline_strategy","decision":"Service worker + local event queue","reason":"Church and rural daycares frequently have spotty WiFi; offline mode is non-negotiable for this segment"},{"step":"qr_token_design","decision":"Signed JWT with 30-second expiry","reason":"Prevents screenshot replay attacks; balances security with ease of use"},{"step":"pdf_reports","decision":"Puppeteer server-side rendering","reason":"Guarantees pixel-perfect state-compliant format; no client-side rendering inconsistency"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$89/mo flat up to 300 children","reason":"Simple pricing directors can approve without per-head math; covers COGS at 15+ accounts"}]', 'submitted', 44, NOW() - INTERVAL '32 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '32 days'),

(2, 7, E'# DropOff+: Smart Daycare Attendance with Parent Communication Hub\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nDropOff+ combines QR-code check-in with a real-time parent communication layer, turning routine attendance into an engagement touchpoint. Beyond logging arrivals and departures, the platform sends parents automatic photo updates, meal reports, and nap logs tied to each check-in session — creating daily value that drives retention for both the daycare and the software. Targeting daycare directors with 150–300 enrolled children, DropOff+ positions itself as an affordable Brightwheel alternative focused exclusively on the daily communication workflow most directors actually use.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| US licensed childcare centers | ~86,000 | NARA 2024 |\n| Parent satisfaction driver #1 (daycare) | Communication quality | J.D. Power Childcare Study 2023 |\n| % of parents who want daily digital updates | 74% | KinderCare parent survey 2023 |\n| Avg. time staff spends on parent communication/day | 45 min | NAEYC operational survey |\n| Brightwheel average subscription cost | $200–$350/mo | Public pricing 2024 |\n| Centers that left Brightwheel citing cost | ~18% of churned accounts | Review mining, G2/Capterra |\n| Childcare worker turnover rate (US) | 30% annually | BLS 2024 |\n| TAM (parent engagement + attendance software) | $890M | MarketsandMarkets 2024 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Brightwheel | All-in-one childcare OS | 150,000+ | Market leader, trusted brand | Expensive, feature bloat for small centers |\n| HiMama | Daily parent reports | 8,000+ | Strong parent UX, photo sharing | Weak director admin tools |\n| Sandbox Childcare | Operations + billing | 3,000+ | Canada-focused, robust billing | Limited US state compliance templates |\n| Kindertales | Documentation + portfolios | 1,500+ | Pedagogical focus | Very slow UI, no real-time check-in |\n| Paper + group text | Manual | ~40,000 centers | Free | No records, unprofessional, FERPA risk |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Diane, 48, Director of Montessori Daycare, Raleigh NC**\nDiane runs a 180-child Montessori center. She left Brightwheel after her billing jumped to $290/mo when she added the messaging module. She loves the parent communication feature but doesn''t need billing software — she uses QuickBooks. She wants something that does daily updates + check-in without forcing her to buy a full suite.\n\n**Persona 2 — Anthony, 35, Operations Manager, 260-Child Daycare Chain (2 locations), Phoenix AZ**\nAnthony manages two campuses. His biggest pain is teachers spending 30 minutes at end-of-day typing individual parent messages. He wants a templated daily report that auto-populates based on check-in time, meal selection, and nap log — staff just taps checkboxes and hits send.\n\n**Persona 3 — Maria, 56, Owner/Director, Spanish-Bilingual Daycare, San Antonio TX**\nMaria''s families are 60% Spanish-speaking. Her current paper sign-in sheet has been filled out in four different languages, which is a compliance nightmare. She needs check-in and parent messages to auto-translate to the parent''s preferred language. This is a feature no competitor offers for her price range.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | QR code check-in/out | Unique per-child QR codes; staff tablet scanner; real-time headcount |\n| P0 | Automated daily parent report | Template-based end-of-day summary auto-sent to parents |\n| P0 | In-app photo sharing (per session) | Teacher uploads 1–3 photos per child per day; parent receives via app |\n| P0 | Attendance log (PDF export) | State-compliant attendance records generated daily |\n| P1 | Meal + nap log | Staff taps checkboxes for meals eaten and nap duration; feeds into daily report |\n| P1 | Multi-language parent messages | Auto-translate daily reports to parent''s language preference (DeepL API) |\n| P1 | Two-way parent messaging | Parents reply to daily reports; messages threaded per child |\n| P2 | Teacher mobile app (iOS + Android) | Native app for faster photo upload and push notification management |\n| P2 | Emergency broadcast message | Director sends instant alert to all parents (weather closure, incident) |\n| P2 | Staff clock-in/out | Same QR infrastructure tracks staff hours for payroll |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Ruby on Rails 7.2 + Sidekiq (background jobs)\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15 + Active Storage (photo management via S3)\n- Translation: DeepL API (10 supported languages)\n- Push Notifications: Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM)\n- Frontend: Rails + Hotwire/Turbo (director dashboard) + React Native (teacher mobile app, M3)\n- Hosting: Heroku (MVP, zero DevOps) → Render.com at scale\n- Auth: Devise + JWT for mobile\n- File Storage: AWS S3 + CloudFront CDN (photos)\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nCheck-in events are processed synchronously via a Rails controller and stored in PostgreSQL. Sidekiq handles all async work: photo resize jobs, translation jobs (DeepL), end-of-day report compilation (triggered at 5:30pm center local time), and FCM push delivery. Photos are uploaded directly to S3 via presigned URLs, bypassing the Rails server for throughput. The daily report builder pulls meal logs, nap logs, and the day''s photos for each child and renders an HTML email + in-app notification. Multi-tenant isolation uses a center_id foreign key on all tables with scoped ActiveRecord queries.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly subscription | $99/mo per center (≤200 children), $149/mo (201–300) | 72% |\n| Photo storage add-on | $9/mo for unlimited photo retention (default: 90 days) | 10% |\n| Multi-language add-on | $19/mo for DeepL translation across all parent messages | 9% |\n| Staff clock-in module | $29/mo add-on | 5% |\n| Implementation & training | One-time $199 | 4% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | QR check-in + headcount + PostgreSQL schema + basic teacher dashboard |\n| M2 | Daily parent report engine + photo sharing + FCM push notifications |\n| M3 | Meal/nap log + PDF attendance export + two-way parent messaging |\n| M4 | DeepL translation + Stripe billing + staff clock-in + 30 pilot centers |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying centers | 25 | 100 |\n| MRR | $2,600 | $11,200 |\n| Daily report delivery rate | >98% | >99.5% |\n| Parent app open rate (daily report) | 55% | 65% |\n| Teacher time saved on communication (min/day) | 30 min | 38 min |\n| Churn rate (monthly) | <4% | <2.5% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Photo privacy concerns (COPPA) | Medium | Critical | Parent consent on enrollment; no photos shared externally; data deletion on request |\n| Translation errors causing miscommunication | Medium | High | DeepL quality is high; add human review flag for medical/emergency messages |\n| Heroku pricing increase | Low | Medium | Containerize early; migrate to Render.com if Heroku costs spike |\n| Teachers resistant to digital workflows | High | Medium | Maximum 3 taps for daily report submission; gamify completion rate for staff |\n| Brightwheel competitive response (price drop) | Medium | Medium | Compete on simplicity and price; Brightwheel''s complexity is a moat for us |\n', '[{"step":"differentiation","decision":"Parent communication + check-in bundle (not billing)","reason":"Directors who left Brightwheel cite billing module as unnecessary complexity; focus on daily workflow they actually use"},{"step":"translation","decision":"DeepL API (not Google Translate)","reason":"DeepL outperforms Google Translate on Spanish/English accuracy by 15–20%; critical for bilingual daycares"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Ruby on Rails + Hotwire","reason":"Rails + Hotwire enables fast iteration with small team; Hotwire''s real-time updates sufficient for dashboard without React complexity"},{"step":"photo_pipeline","decision":"S3 presigned upload + CloudFront CDN","reason":"Keeps photo bandwidth off app server; CDN ensures fast load for parents regardless of location"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$99–$149/mo tiered by enrollment","reason":"Below Brightwheel at all tiers; simple enough for directors to approve without committee sign-off"},{"step":"mobile_approach","decision":"Web-first M1-M3, React Native app M4+","reason":"Ship faster with web; native app for teachers adds value in M4 when retention data confirms photo upload is key workflow"}]', 'submitted', 36, NOW() - INTERVAL '28 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '28 days'),

(2, 11, E'# SafeArrive: Compliance-First Daycare Check-In for Multi-Site Operators\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nSafeArrive is a kiosk-based daycare check-in system designed for multi-site childcare operators and franchise groups who face audit risk across all locations simultaneously. Rather than a phone-centric QR flow, SafeArrive deploys an iPad kiosk at each entrance with face-recognition-assisted identity verification — parents are recognized on approach, reducing check-in to under 8 seconds. Centralized audit dashboards give compliance officers a real-time view of every location''s attendance status, incident flags, and state-report readiness. The platform targets daycare operators managing 3–8 sites with 150–300 children each.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Multi-site childcare operators (3–8 locations, US) | ~4,200 groups | Childcare.gov operator registry 2024 |\n| Average compliance audit fine (multi-site) | $1,800–$15,000 | State licensing penalty schedules |\n| % of multi-site operators with unified check-in | ~19% | NAEYC enterprise survey 2023 |\n| Average enrollment per site (target segment) | 180–280 children | IBISWorld childcare report 2024 |\n| iPad kiosk hardware cost (amortized 3yr) | $12/mo per kiosk | Apple iPad 10th gen + stand |\n| Staff time lost to manual attendance reconciliation | 1.5 hrs/day per site | NAEYC operational data |\n| Childcare compliance software market (US) | $340M | Verified Market Research 2024 |\n| YoY growth rate (childcare tech) | 14.2% CAGR | Same source |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Brightwheel | All-in-one childcare OS | 150,000+ | Dominant market share | No face recognition; poor multi-site compliance view |\n| Procare Solutions | Billing + compliance | 37,000+ | Deep compliance templates | Dated UI; per-module pricing gets expensive |\n| iClassPro | Activity classes + check-in | 10,000+ | Kiosk-friendly UI | Sports-class focus; weak childcare compliance |\n| Verkada | Physical security + access control | 20,000+ enterprises | Hardware-grade reliability | Not childcare-specific; $500+/mo per site |\n| LineLeader (ChildcareCRM) | Enrollment + ops | 5,000+ | Strong enrollment funnel | No attendance or check-in module |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Brenda, 54, VP of Operations, 6-Site Childcare Chain, Minneapolis MN**\nBrenda oversees compliance across six licensed centers. She experienced a $4,200 fine last year when one site''s director forgot to submit monthly attendance reconciliation to the state. She needs a system that auto-generates and auto-submits state reports, removing human error from the compliance chain entirely.\n\n**Persona 2 — Thomas, 42, Franchise Owner of 4 KinderCare-affiliated Sites, Seattle WA**\nThomas''s franchise agreement requires him to maintain specific staff-to-child ratios in real time. If a teacher calls in sick and no substitute arrives, he needs an alert before licensing ratios are breached — not after an inspector visits. Real-time ratio monitoring is his top priority.\n\n**Persona 3 — Angela, 38, Director of a Head Start Program, Detroit MI**\nAngela''s federally-funded Head Start program requires detailed attendance documentation for subsidy reimbursement. Every missed signature costs her program reimbursement dollars. She needs the check-in system to generate subsidy-billing-ready attendance exports in the exact format required by the Michigan DHHS portal.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | iPad kiosk check-in (QR + PIN fallback) | Entrance kiosk with QR scan; PIN entry for parents without QR |\n| P0 | Face recognition-assisted ID (optional) | On-device ML model suggests parent identity on approach; staff confirms |\n| P0 | Real-time staff-to-child ratio monitor | Per-room ratio calculated live; alert if approaching licensing threshold |\n| P0 | Multi-site compliance dashboard | Central view of all sites: headcounts, ratio status, report readiness |\n| P0 | State-format attendance report generation | Auto-generate PDF in correct state format; one-click submission log |\n| P1 | Authorized pickup photo registry | Photo ID stored per authorized adult; displayed on pickup scan for visual verification |\n| P1 | Subsidy billing export | Export attendance in CCAP/Head Start format for state reimbursement portals |\n| P1 | Incident logging integration | Flag check-in sessions with incident notes; feeds into state incident reports |\n| P2 | Hardware monitoring | Alert if kiosk goes offline or battery drops below 20% |\n| P2 | API for third-party payroll systems | Export staff clock-in data to ADP, Gusto |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Go 1.22 + Gin (high-concurrency, low-latency API)\n- Database: PostgreSQL 16 (with RLS for multi-tenant isolation)\n- Face Recognition: Apple Vision framework (on-device, privacy-preserving; no photos leave iPad)\n- Kiosk App: Swift (iPadOS) — native for hardware reliability\n- Compliance Report Engine: Go + WeasyPrint (HTML→PDF with state-specific templates)\n- Push Alerts: APNs (iPad kiosk) + Twilio (SMS to site director)\n- Frontend (web dashboard): Next.js 15 + Tailwind CSS\n- Hosting: AWS ECS + RDS PostgreSQL + CloudFront\n- Auth: Auth0 multi-tenant with role-based access (site director, ops manager, compliance officer)\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nEach iPad kiosk runs a native Swift app that operates fully offline, queueing check-in events in Core Data and syncing to the backend via REST when connectivity is available. Face recognition runs entirely on-device using Apple Vision — no facial images are transmitted to the server, only a confirmation flag. The Go backend aggregates events from all sites, computes real-time ratios via a materialized view refreshed every 30 seconds, and serves the Next.js compliance dashboard. State report generation is a Go service that reads a JSON template per state (50 templates maintained) and renders PDF via WeasyPrint. Multi-tenant RLS ensures a site director can only query their own site''s data.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Per-site subscription | $149/site/mo (includes kiosk app license) | 58% |\n| Compliance officer dashboard | $199/mo flat (unlimited sites read access) | 18% |\n| Hardware bundle | iPad 10th gen + kiosk stand: $349 one-time (at cost + $20 margin) | 10% |\n| Subsidy billing export module | $49/site/mo add-on | 9% |\n| Professional implementation | $499 per account (multi-site setup + staff training) | 5% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | iPadOS kiosk app (QR + PIN) + Go backend + PostgreSQL multi-tenant schema |\n| M2 | Real-time ratio monitor + multi-site dashboard + attendance PDF generation |\n| M3 | Face recognition (on-device) + authorized pickup photo registry + Twilio alerts |\n| M4 | Subsidy billing export + Auth0 RBAC + compliance officer portal + 10 pilot sites |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying site count | 20 | 70 |\n| MRR | $3,200 | $12,400 |\n| Check-in time per child (avg) | <10 seconds | <8 seconds |\n| Ratio alert false-positive rate | <3% | <1% |\n| State report generation accuracy | 100% | 100% |\n| Compliance fine incidents at client sites | 0 | 0 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| State report format changes | High | High | Template-driven system with 48hr update SLA in contract |\n| Face recognition bias/accuracy issues | Medium | High | Optional feature; PIN fallback always available; Apple Vision is state-of-art for iOS |\n| iPad hardware failure at site | Medium | Medium | Hardware replacement SLA; paper backup protocol in onboarding |\n| Multi-tenant data isolation breach | Low | Critical | RLS + automated integration tests + quarterly security audit |\n| Head Start/CCAP portal format changes | Medium | High | Dedicated compliance engineer monitors federal childcare policy; 30-day update SLA |\n', '[{"step":"target_segment","decision":"Multi-site operators (3–8 sites)","reason":"Higher ACV; compliance risk is exponentially higher for multi-site operators; one sale covers multiple sites"},{"step":"hardware_strategy","decision":"iPad kiosk with native Swift app","reason":"Native app gives offline reliability and access to Apple Vision for face recognition; web PWA too unreliable for entrance kiosk"},{"step":"face_recognition","decision":"On-device Apple Vision (no server-side)","reason":"COPPA and FERPA compliance requires no biometric data leaving the device; Apple Vision accuracy meets enterprise bar"},{"step":"compliance_engine","decision":"50 state-specific PDF templates","reason":"Each state has unique attendance format; template system lets us add states incrementally without code changes"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Per-site $149/mo + compliance dashboard $199/mo","reason":"Multi-site operators budget per-location; compliance dashboard is separate SKU that ops managers control"},{"step":"go_to_market","decision":"Target Head Start programs and KinderCare-affiliated franchises","reason":"Federal funding creates budget certainty; franchise compliance requirements create urgent, non-discretionary demand"}]', 'submitted', 29, NOW() - INTERVAL '35 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '36 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '35 days');

