INSERT INTO contributions (idea_id, author_id, content, decision_log, status, view_count, submitted_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES
(4, 6, E'# RepTrack: Session Management Platform for Independent Personal Trainers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nRepTrack is a mobile-first SaaS tool that helps independent personal trainers manage the full client lifecycle: session booking, check-in confirmation, package tracking (sessions remaining), and automated renewal reminders before a package expires. By consolidating what trainers currently manage across Google Calendar, spreadsheets, and text messages, RepTrack reduces administrative overhead to under 10 minutes per day. The platform targets trainers with 20–50 active clients operating independently at gyms, studios, or outdoors.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Certified personal trainers (US, self-employed) | ~112,000 | BLS Occupational Outlook 2024 |\n| Avg. active clients per independent trainer | 25–45 | NASM industry report 2024 |\n| Avg. session package size | 10 sessions at $65–$90/session | Internal survey n=150 |\n| % of trainers using spreadsheets for tracking | 62% | Mindbody SMB fitness survey 2023 |\n| % of trainers who lose clients due to poor follow-up | 38% self-reported | ACE Fitness business survey |\n| Avg. trainer revenue lost to package expiry without renewal | $520/client/year | Calculated from survey data |\n| US personal training market size | $14.8B | IBISWorld 2024 |\n| TAM (scheduling + session mgmt for indie trainers) | $380M | Internal sizing |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Mindbody | Studio management suite | 65,000+ studios | Full-featured, brand recognition | $139+/mo, designed for studios not solo trainers |\n| Trainerize | Online coaching platform | 70,000+ trainers | Great workout delivery | No in-person session tracking, no package mgmt |\n| My PT Hub | Training + nutrition plans | 35,000+ | All-in-one | Weak booking/check-in workflow |\n| Acuity Scheduling | Appointment booking | 100,000+ | Easy to set up | No session package tracking |\n| Google Calendar + Venmo | Manual | Most indie trainers | Free | Zero automation, no package visibility |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Jake, 29, Independent Personal Trainer, Denver CO**\nJake trains 35 clients per week at a 24 Hour Fitness where he rents floor space. He tracks sessions in a notebook and Venmo''s clients after each 10-session pack is sold. He regularly discovers clients are on session 9 only when they show up for what they think is session 10. He loses ~3 renewal conversations per month because he doesn''t follow up proactively.\n\n**Persona 2 — Megan, 34, Outdoor Bootcamp Trainer, Austin TX**\nMegan runs group bootcamp sessions and 1-on-1 training outdoors. She has 48 active clients. Her pain: clients pay via Zelle or cash and she manually tracks who owes what in Notes app. She needs a system that works without WiFi (outdoor sessions) and syncs when she gets back to the car.\n\n**Persona 3 — Carlos, 44, Strength Coach at Corporate Gym, Chicago IL**\nCarlos has a waiting list of 55 clients. He struggles with no-shows — clients who cancel last minute mean a dead hour. He wants automated 24-hour reminder texts that require confirmation, and a waitlist system that fills the slot if the primary client cancels.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Client profile + session package management | Name, contact, active package (type, sessions total, used, remaining) |\n| P0 | Session booking (trainer-initiated) | Book a session slot; client receives SMS confirmation |\n| P0 | Check-in (one tap) | Trainer taps "Session Complete" to decrement package counter |\n| P0 | Package renewal reminder | Auto-SMS/email when 2 sessions remain; include payment link |\n| P0 | Dashboard: upcoming sessions + low-package alerts | Daily trainer view |\n| P1 | Client payment tracking | Log payment method (Venmo, Zelle, card); flag unpaid sessions |\n| P1 | 24-hour session reminder to client | Auto-SMS 24hr before; require reply confirm/cancel |\n| P1 | Waitlist management | Cancelled slot auto-notifies waitlisted clients |\n| P2 | Workout log per session | Optional notes/exercises logged per session; client can view history |\n| P2 | Progress photo storage | Trainer uploads client progress photos; client accesses via link |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Go 1.22 + Echo v4\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15\n- SMS: Twilio (reminders, confirmations, renewal alerts)\n- Email: Resend\n- Frontend: React Native (iOS + Android) — trainer app\n- Client portal: Next.js 15 (mobile web, no download required)\n- Offline sync: React Native + SQLite (WatermelonDB) with background sync\n- Hosting: Fly.io (backend) + Vercel (client portal)\n- Auth: JWT + biometric (Face ID/fingerprint) for trainer app\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nThe trainer mobile app uses WatermelonDB for offline-first session logging — all session completions are written locally and synced to the Go backend when connectivity is restored. Package counters are managed as an event log (session_events table) rather than a mutable counter, enabling audit trail and idempotent replay. Twilio reminder jobs are scheduled as PostgreSQL cron jobs (pg_cron extension) rather than a separate scheduler service, keeping the infrastructure minimal. The client portal is a stateless Next.js app that reads session history and package balance via API.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly subscription | $29/mo (up to 30 clients), $49/mo (31–60 clients) | 78% |\n| SMS credits | $7/mo for 300 SMS (Twilio passthrough + margin) | 14% |\n| Progress photo storage add-on | $5/mo for unlimited photo storage | 5% |\n| Annual plan discount | Pay 10 months, get 12 | (reduces churn, not additive revenue) |\n| Referral program | $20 credit per trainer referred | 3% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | Client profiles + package management + session check-in (Go API + React Native MVP) |\n| M2 | Twilio renewal reminders + 24hr session reminders + basic dashboard |\n| M3 | Offline sync (WatermelonDB) + waitlist management + client portal (Next.js) |\n| M4 | Stripe billing + payment tracking + workout log + onboard 60 pilot trainers |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying trainers | 55 | 220 |\n| MRR | $1,900 | $8,800 |\n| Session check-in time (trainer tap to logged) | <5 seconds | <5 seconds |\n| Package renewal SMS conversion rate | 42% | 55% |\n| Trainer-reported no-show reduction | -30% | -40% |\n| Monthly churn | <3% | <2% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| React Native build complexity for solo dev | Medium | Medium | Use Expo managed workflow; avoid custom native modules in MVP |\n| Trainers use multiple apps and don''t switch | High | High | Offer CSV import from Google Sheets/Excel; 5-min onboarding |\n| Twilio SMS delivery failures | Low | Medium | Email fallback for all reminders; Twilio SLA 99.95% |\n| Gym bans third-party trainer software | Low | Low | App is trainer-owned; no gym integration needed |\n| Client no-shows still happen despite reminders | High (behavioral) | Low | Reminders reduce no-shows; trainers understand they can''t be eliminated |\n', '[{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Go + Echo backend with React Native frontend","reason":"Go matches existing Claway backend expertise; React Native gives cross-platform mobile app without maintaining two codebases"},{"step":"offline_first","decision":"WatermelonDB for offline sync","reason":"Outdoor and basement gym trainers frequently have no signal; session logging must work offline"},{"step":"package_tracking","decision":"Event log model (not mutable counter)","reason":"Prevents race conditions; gives full audit trail; trainers can dispute session counts with evidence"},{"step":"scheduler","decision":"pg_cron (no external scheduler)","reason":"Keeps infrastructure minimal for MVP; pg_cron handles daily reminder job at scale up to 10,000 trainers"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$29/$49 tiered by client count","reason":"Below Mindbody at every tier; aligns cost with trainer''s revenue; $29 is below expense-report threshold"}]', 'submitted', 48, NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '34 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days'),

(4, 10, E'# CoachDesk: Client Retention CRM for Personal Trainers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nCoachDesk approaches personal trainer management as a client retention problem, not a scheduling problem. While competitors focus on booking, CoachDesk centers on package expiry prediction, churn risk scoring, and proactive outreach — helping trainers identify clients likely to drop off before their next purchase decision, and giving them the right message at the right time to retain them. Built for trainers with 20–50 active clients, CoachDesk delivers the kind of CRM intelligence that enterprise gym chains use, at $39/mo for independent operators.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Self-employed personal trainers (US) | ~112,000 | BLS 2024 |\n| Avg. client lifetime with one trainer | 8.4 months | IHRSA retention study 2023 |\n| % of trainer revenue from existing clients | 74% | NASM business survey |\n| Cost to acquire new client vs retain existing | $140 vs $22 | Internal trainer survey |\n| Avg. package renewal rate without proactive outreach | 41% | Mindbody benchmark data |\n| Avg. package renewal rate with automated follow-up | 67% | Same source |\n| Revenue uplift from 26-point renewal rate increase | +$8,400/yr per trainer | Calculated at $65/session, 5-session pkg |\n| TAM (retention + CRM tools for independent fitness) | $290M | Mordor Intelligence 2024 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Trainerize | Online coaching delivery | 70,000+ | Workout plans, nutrition | No CRM, no retention analytics |\n| Mindbody | Studio management | 65,000+ studios | Full-featured | Over-engineered for solo trainers |\n| PTminder | Session + package tracking | 12,000+ | Affordable, simple | No churn prediction, no CRM layer |\n| Hubspot Free | Generic CRM | Millions | Free, powerful | Not fitness-specific; overkill |\n| Excel + Calendly | Manual | ~60% trainers | Free | No analytics, no automation |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Brittany, 31, Strength & Conditioning Trainer, Seattle WA**\nBrittany has 42 active clients. She knows she loses about 5 clients per quarter to drop-off, but she can never predict who. By the time she notices a client has gone quiet, they''ve already ghosted. She would pay for a tool that tells her "Sarah hasn''t booked in 3 weeks and her package expires in 2 sessions — reach out now" before it''s too late.\n\n**Persona 2 — Derek, 38, Bootcamp + HIIT Trainer, Miami FL**\nDerek runs both group classes and 1-on-1 sessions. He tracks groups differently from 1-on-1 packages. He wants a dashboard that clearly separates his revenue streams and tells him which clients are most valuable (highest LTV) so he can prioritize his energy.\n\n**Persona 3 — Amanda, 26, New Certified Trainer, Nashville TN**\nAmanda just got certified and is building her first client roster. She has 18 clients and is overwhelmed by the business side. She wants a tool that tells her what to do next — which client to follow up with, when to send a renewal offer — so she can focus on training, not administration.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Client profile + session package log | Contact info, active package, session history, payment history |\n| P0 | Churn risk score | ML-light scoring based on booking frequency drop, sessions remaining, days since last session |\n| P0 | Daily action queue | "Do this today" list: follow up with Sarah, send renewal to Mike, check in with Derek |\n| P0 | Package renewal automation | Auto-send renewal offer when 2–3 sessions remain |\n| P1 | Client LTV dashboard | Revenue per client, avg. package count, retention duration |\n| P1 | Session check-in (one tap) | Decrement package counter; log session date |\n| P1 | 1-click outreach templates | Pre-written SMS/email for renewal, check-in, win-back |\n| P2 | Group vs 1-on-1 revenue split | Track both revenue streams separately |\n| P2 | Referral tracking | Log which clients referred new clients; reward system |\n| P2 | Goal milestone alerts | Alert trainer when client hits a tracked goal (weight, reps) |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Python 3.12 + FastAPI\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15 + Redis\n- Churn scoring: Scikit-learn (logistic regression on session frequency + package velocity features)\n- SMS: Twilio\n- Email: Postmark\n- Frontend: Vue.js 3 + Quasar Framework (cross-platform PWA: works as web + installable mobile)\n- Background jobs: Celery + Redis\n- Hosting: Railway.app\n- Auth: Magic link (Postmark) for trainer login\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nThe churn scoring model is a lightweight logistic regression trained on synthetic trainer data (days_since_last_session, sessions_remaining, avg_sessions_per_week, packages_completed). It re-scores all clients nightly via a Celery beat job and writes risk_score (0–100) to the client record. The daily action queue is a SQL query ordered by risk_score DESC + days_since_contact ASC, surfaced as the trainer''s homepage. Outreach templates are stored as parameterized strings in PostgreSQL; trainers can edit them. The Quasar PWA compiles to a web app that can be installed to the trainer''s phone home screen without app store submission, dramatically reducing distribution friction.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly subscription | $39/mo (all features, up to 60 clients) | 76% |\n| SMS credits | $8/mo for 400 SMS | 13% |\n| Annual plan | $390/yr (save $78) | (reduces churn) |\n| Coach certification partner listings | $29/mo for NASM/ACE certified coach badge + directory listing | 7% |\n| Group class add-on | $9/mo for unlimited group session tracking | 4% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | Client profiles + session log + package tracking + daily action queue |\n| M2 | Churn risk scoring (rule-based first, ML in M3) + Twilio renewal reminders |\n| M3 | ML churn model + LTV dashboard + 1-click outreach templates + PWA packaging |\n| M4 | Stripe billing + group class tracking + referral tracking + 70 pilot trainers |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying trainers | 60 | 230 |\n| MRR | $2,500 | $10,200 |\n| Churn risk model precision (flagged → actually churned) | 55% | 68% |\n| Package renewal rate (trainers using reminders) | 58% | 67% |\n| Daily action queue completion rate | 45% | 60% |\n| Trainer-reported monthly revenue increase | +$600 avg | +$1,100 avg |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| ML model requires too much training data initially | High | Medium | Start with rule-based heuristics (days_since_session > 14 = risk); layer ML when 500+ clients in system |\n| Trainers don''t log sessions consistently | High | High | One-tap check-in; reminder to trainers if no session logged in 48hrs |\n| PWA not accepted as "real app" by trainers | Medium | Medium | Offer "Add to Home Screen" onboarding tutorial; PWA looks native on iOS/Android |\n| Postmark/Twilio API failures | Low | Medium | Retry with exponential backoff; email fallback for SMS; in-app notification as tertiary |\n| Competing with free (Google Sheets) | High | Medium | Make ROI concrete: "You recovered $420 this month from renewal reminders" |\n', '[{"step":"core_differentiator","decision":"Retention CRM + churn scoring (not just scheduling)","reason":"Scheduling is table stakes; churn prediction is defensible IP and directly tied to trainer revenue"},{"step":"churn_model","decision":"Rule-based first, ML in M3","reason":"Logistic regression needs data; rule-based (days_since_session thresholds) works immediately and trains users to act on scores"},{"step":"frontend","decision":"Vue + Quasar PWA (not React Native)","reason":"Quasar compiles to installable PWA; avoids app store submission; Vue has lower learning curve than React for solo dev"},{"step":"action_queue","decision":"Daily prioritized to-do list as homepage","reason":"Trainers are overwhelmed by options; prescriptive queue reduces decision fatigue and drives daily active use"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Flat $39/mo (no tiers)","reason":"Simplicity; under $50/mo is impulse-buy for trainers; LTV analysis shows flat pricing maximizes M6 MRR"},{"step":"gtm","decision":"Partner with NASM/ACE certification programs","reason":"New trainers are highest-intent moment; certification completion = business launch = need for tools"}]', 'submitted', 62, NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days'),

(4, 15, E'# PackPass: Simple Session Package Manager with Client Self-Service Portal\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nPackPass strips personal trainer management down to its absolute core: tracking session packages and letting clients see exactly how many sessions they have left. The client-facing self-service portal is the product''s defining feature — clients log in via a link texted to them, view their package balance, book their next session, and pay for a renewal without ever needing to call or text their trainer. This reduces the administrative back-and-forth that consumes 45 minutes of an average trainer''s day. PackPass targets trainers with 20–50 clients who want maximum simplicity at minimum cost.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Independent personal trainers (US) | ~112,000 | BLS 2024 |\n| Avg. daily admin time (booking + billing + follow-up) | 45–75 min | NASM business productivity survey |\n| % of trainers who handle renewals via text message | 71% | Internal survey n=200 |\n| Client no-show rate (no reminder) | 22% | Mindbody fitness benchmark |\n| Client no-show rate (with 24hr reminder) | 8% | Same source |\n| Stripe checkout conversion rate (mobile, link-based) | 76% | Stripe public data |\n| Avg. trainer willingness to pay for time savings | $35–$55/mo | Conjoint analysis, n=120 trainers |\n| % trainers who accept cash/Venmo (no formal checkout) | 68% | NASM survey |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Focus | Users | Strengths | Weaknesses |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| PTminder | Session + package tracking | 12,000+ | Affordable | Dated UI, no client self-service portal |\n| Acuity Scheduling | Appointment booking | 100,000+ | Beautiful client-facing booking | No session package tracking |\n| Vagaro | Grooming + fitness management | 70,000+ | Strong features | Designed for studios, complex for solo trainers |\n| Square Appointments | Booking + payments | 500,000+ | Free tier | No package/session counter |\n| Calendly + Venmo | Manual combo | ~40% trainers | Free, familiar | No session tracking, no renewal automation |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Tori, 27, New Personal Trainer, Phoenix AZ**\nTori has 22 clients and is 6 months into her first year. She handles everything via Instagram DMs and Venmo. She has accidentally double-booked clients twice. She wants something dead-simple that she can set up in an afternoon and that makes her look professional to clients without spending more than $30/mo.\n\n**Persona 2 — Marcus, 45, Semi-Retired Trainer, Fort Lauderdale FL**\nMarcus trains 30 longtime clients, most of them 50+ years old. His clients are not tech-savvy. He needs a client portal that works on an older iPhone without confusing them. Large text, one button, no login passwords — just a link that shows their balance and a "Book Next Session" button.\n\n**Persona 3 — Jasmine, 33, Prenatal Fitness Specialist, Boston MA**\nJasmine sells 8-session prenatal packages at $95/session. Her clients are highly motivated and organized. They want to see their remaining sessions, access invoice PDFs for their FSA reimbursement, and book sessions up to 4 weeks in advance. Her current system (Acuity + manual spreadsheet) cannot handle package counts.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Session package creation + assignment | Define package (name, session count, price); assign to client |\n| P0 | One-tap session check-in | Trainer taps to mark session complete; counter decrements |\n| P0 | Client self-service portal | Client views package balance, upcoming sessions, session history via SMS link |\n| P0 | Automated renewal prompt (SMS) | Auto-text when 2 sessions remain; includes Stripe payment link |\n| P0 | Stripe payment integration | Client buys renewal package via hosted Stripe checkout |\n| P1 | Appointment booking (client-initiated) | Client books from available slots in trainer''s calendar |\n| P1 | 24hr session reminder | Auto-SMS to client day before; one-tap confirm/cancel |\n| P1 | Invoice PDF generation | Auto-generate invoice per package purchase (for FSA/insurance) |\n| P2 | Waitlist (cancelled slot → waiting client) | Automatic notification to next waitlisted client |\n| P2 | Multi-trainer support | Studio owner can manage 2–5 trainers under one account |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Tech Stack:**\n- Backend: Ruby on Rails 7.2 + Sidekiq\n- Database: PostgreSQL 15\n- Payments: Stripe Checkout + Stripe Webhooks\n- SMS: Twilio\n- PDF invoices: Prawn (Ruby PDF library)\n- Frontend: Rails + Hotwire + Tailwind CSS (trainer dashboard) + mobile-optimized Rails views (client portal)\n- Hosting: Render.com\n- Auth: Devise (trainer login), signed URL tokens (client portal — no login required)\n\n**Architecture Description:**\nThe client portal is entirely stateless on the client side — a signed URL (HMAC-SHA256, 7-day expiry) encodes client_id and trainer_id. When the client clicks the link, the Rails server validates the signature, queries the session balance, and renders a mobile-first HTML page. No client account creation required. Stripe Checkout handles all payment flow; a Stripe webhook updates the package record upon successful payment. Twilio reminders are Sidekiq jobs scheduled at booking time. Prawn generates invoice PDFs server-side and attaches them to the confirmation email via Action Mailer. The entire system is a conventional Rails monolith — no microservices, no queue beyond Sidekiq.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Source | Model | Expected % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly subscription | $25/mo (solo trainer, up to 50 clients) | 70% |\n| Stripe payment processing (pass-through) | 2.9% + $0.30 per renewal transaction (Stripe standard) | (not revenue; trainer absorbs) |\n| SMS add-on | $6/mo for 250 SMS beyond included 50 free | 15% |\n| Multi-trainer add-on | $15/mo per additional trainer seat | 10% |\n| Annual plan | $240/yr ($25 savings) | (reduces churn) |\n| Invoice + FSA export add-on | $5/mo for branded PDF invoices | 5% |\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Month | Milestone |\n|---|---|\n| M1 | Package management + check-in + PostgreSQL schema + basic trainer dashboard |\n| M2 | Client portal (signed URL) + Stripe Checkout + renewal SMS trigger |\n| M3 | Calendar booking (client-initiated) + 24hr reminders + PDF invoice generation |\n| M4 | Stripe billing (trainer subscription) + waitlist + multi-trainer + 80 pilot trainers |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M6 Target |\n|---|---|---|\n| Paying trainers | 70 | 280 |\n| MRR | $1,900 | $8,200 |\n| Client portal link click rate | 65% | 72% |\n| Renewal completion rate via Stripe link | 58% | 68% |\n| Trainer onboarding time (signup to first check-in) | <15 min | <10 min |\n| Monthly churn | <2.5% | <1.8% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Trainers reluctant to charge via Stripe (prefer Venmo) | High | Medium | Make Venmo/Zelle manual payment logging available; Stripe is optional |\n| Signed URL security concerns | Low | Low | HMAC-SHA256 with 7-day expiry; no sensitive data in URL params |\n| Render.com downtime affecting bookings | Low | Medium | 99.9% SLA; add status page; email fallback for critical reminders |\n| Feature creep requests from trainers | High | Medium | Strict "PackPass does packages" positioning; redirect complex requests to Mindbody |\n| Stripe webhook delivery failures | Low | High | Idempotency key on all webhook handlers; manual reconciliation report |\n', '[{"step":"core_philosophy","decision":"Radical simplicity — do one thing perfectly","reason":"Market is full of over-featured tools; trainers with 20–50 clients need 5% of Mindbody''s features at 10% of the price"},{"step":"client_portal","decision":"Signed URL (no client account)","reason":"Eliminates login friction for clients; no password reset support burden; clients just click a link"},{"step":"payments","decision":"Stripe Checkout (hosted)","reason":"Hosted checkout handles PCI compliance; trainer doesn''t need to think about payment security; mobile conversion rate 76%"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Rails monolith (no microservices)","reason":"Solo dev or small team; Rails monolith ships faster; Sidekiq covers all async needs"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$25/mo — lowest viable","reason":"Under $30/mo is below expense threshold for most trainers; volume strategy: 1,000 trainers at $25 beats 100 at $100"},{"step":"gtm","decision":"Instagram + TikTok short-form content targeting trainers","reason":"Personal trainers are heavy Instagram/TikTok users; video demos of the client portal resonate better than cold email"}]', 'submitted', 35, NOW() - INTERVAL '40 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '41 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '40 days');

